:::summary
The Bill of Rights — the first ten amendments to the United States Constitution, ratified on December 15, 1791 — is the foundational charter of American individual liberties. Drafted by James Madison and insisted upon by Anti-Federalists as the price of ratifying the Constitution, these amendments guarantee freedom of speech, religion, press, and assembly; the right to bear arms; protections against arbitrary search and seizure; the right to a fair trial; and the reservation of unspecified powers to the states and people.
:::

